    subcategory: 'Technology',
    definition: 'Google (now Alphabet Inc.) started as a research project by Larry Page and Sergey Brin at Stanford University in 1996. Their innovation was PageRank, an algorithm that ranked web pages by the number and quality of links pointing to them — treating links as "votes" for a page\'s authority. This was far superior to existing search engines that relied on keyword density and metadata. Google\'s business model is built on a remarkable flywheel: Search attracts billions of users → user attention is monetized through advertising → ad revenue funds massive infrastructure and R&D → better products attract more users. Google captures nearly 40% of all digital advertising spending globally ($237 billion in 2023). The key products: Google Search (90%+ market share), YouTube (2.5B users, $35B ad revenue), Google Cloud ($35B revenue), Android (3B+ devices), Google Maps (1B+ users), and Gmail (1.8B users). Google\'s advertising system is the most sophisticated in the world: AdWords (now Google Ads) uses a real-time auction where advertisers bid on keywords, and Google\'s algorithm determines ad placement based on bid amount AND ad quality (relevance, click-through rate, landing page experience). This "pay-for-performance" model disrupted traditional advertising (newspapers, Yellow Pages) because advertisers only pay when users click. Google\'s competitive advantages are immense: (1) Data moat — billions of searches per day generate data that improves search quality, which attracts more users, which generates more data. (2) Scale economics — Google\'s infrastructure (thousands of servers in data centers worldwide) costs billions but is shared across products, making marginal costs near zero. (3) Network effects — Google Search gets better the more people use it because click-through data trains the ranking algorithm. The rise of AI poses the greatest challenge to Google\'s search dominance. ChatGPT and other LLMs offer direct answers instead of links, potentially decimating the ad-supported search model. Google has responded with its own AI products (Gemini, Search Generative Experience) but faces an innovator\'s dilemma: cannibalizing its $237B search ad business is painful.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Google organizes the world\'s information and makes it accessible to everyone for free, then makes $237 billion a year by showing ads that are so relevant you often do not mind clicking them.',
