    category: 'Case Studies',
    subcategory: 'Technology',
    definition: 'Microsoft is the world\'s largest software company, founded by Bill Gates and Paul Allen in 1975 with the vision of "a computer on every desk and in every home." The company achieved dominance through two strategic masterstrokes: the MS-DOS deal with IBM (1981) and the Windows operating system (1985). By licensing software to IBM (rather than selling it outright), Microsoft retained the rights to license MS-DOS to other manufacturers, creating the PC-compatible ecosystem that made Microsoft the default software provider for 90%+ of computers. Microsoft\'s business model evolved through three eras: Era 1 — Software Licensing (1975-2013): Microsoft sold Windows and Office as perpetual licenses for $100-500 per copy. Gross margins exceeded 80% because the marginal cost of producing software was near zero. This created one of the most profitable business models in history — by 2000, Microsoft had a $600B market cap with 75%+ net profit margins. Era 2 — The Lost Decade (2000-2013): Microsoft missed the internet (Bing vs. Google), mobile (Windows Phone vs. iPhone/Android), search, social media, and hardware (Zune vs. iPod). The company stagnated under Steve Ballmer, though Windows and Office continued generating enormous profits. Era 3 — The Nadella Transformation (2014-Present): Satya Nadella became CEO and executed one of the greatest corporate turnarounds in history. He shifted Microsoft from "Windows-first" to "cloud-first, mobile-first" strategy. The key moves: (1) Embracing open source — Microsoft released .NET Core, TypeScript, VS Code, and joined Linux Foundation. (2) Azure investment — Microsoft invested tens of billions in cloud infrastructure, making Azure the #2 cloud provider (behind AWS) with $80B+ annual revenue. (3) Office 365 transition — converting Office from a one-time purchase ($150) to a subscription ($100/year per user), increasing recurring revenue and customer lifetime value. (4) LinkedIn acquisition — $26.2 billion (2016), the largest Microsoft acquisition, adding a professional social network to the portfolio. (5) GitHub acquisition — $7.5 billion (2018), embracing open source developers. (6) OpenAI investment — $13+ billion (2023-2024), positioning Microsoft at the center of the AI revolution. Under Nadella, Microsoft\'s market cap rose from $300 billion to $2.5+ trillion, making it one of the most valuable companies in the world.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Microsoft makes the software that runs most of the world\'s computers and — after almost missing the internet and mobile revolutions — reinvented itself as a cloud computing giant under CEO Satya Nadella.',
